  <td class="diff-deletedline"><div>''War and Peace'' is well known as being one of the longest novels ever written, though not the longest. It is actually the seventh longest novel ever written in a Latin or Cyrillic based alphabet and is subdivided into four books or volumes, each with sub parts containing many chapters.{{cn|date=February 2014}}</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">+</td>
  <td class="diff-addedline"><div>''War and Peace'' is well known as being one of the longest novels ever written, though not the longest. It is actually the seventh longest novel ever written in a Latin or Cyrillic based alphabet and is subdivided into four books or volumes, each with sub parts containing many chapters.{{cn|date=February 2014}}<ins class="diffchange diffchange-inline">  The book has become culturally symbolic as the quintessential "long novel," and a cliché paralleling the book with protracted time or long works of literature has sprung up around it.  For example, in Steve Sohmer's 1987 novel, "''Favourite Son''," a character tells his date that she is taking so long to prepare for the evening that he has decided to read "War and Peace" while he waits.  When he tells her that he is up to the part where Smerdyakov commits suicide, she laughs and tells him him that detail is from Dostoyevsky's "The Brothers Karamazov," not "War and Peace."</ins></div></td>
</tr>
